{{Infobox person | name = Otoyo no Mikoto | image = | image_size = | caption = | era = [[Kofun period]] | birth_date = Unknown | death_date = Unknown | renamed = | other_names = Kotoyo no Mikoto, Koto no Mikoto | posthumous_name = | deity_name = | Buddhist_name = | burial_place = Possibly {{ill|Shiratori-zuka Kofun (Nagoya)|lt=Shiratori-zuka Kofun|ja|白鳥塚古墳 (名古屋市)|12=draft}} | Rank = [[Kokuzō]] | lord = Possibly [[Emperor Keikō]] | clan = [[Owari clan]] | parents = | siblings = | spouse = [[Mashikito Hime]] | children = {{ill|Takeinadane|fr}}, [[Miyazu-hime]]|notable_facts =|12=draft}}
'''Otoyo no Mikoto''' (乎止与命) was a [[Kofun period]] [[Kuni no miyatsuko|local chieftain]] and one of the [[Owari clan|Owari Kokuzō]].
== Overview == In the ''[[Kokuzō Hongi]]'', he is referred to as '''Kotoyo no Mikoto''', while in the ''[[Shinsen Shōjiroku]]'', he is recorded as '''Koto no Mikoto'''<ref>"Kawachi Province, Kami-betsu, Tenson, Owari no Muraji" in the ''Shinsen Shōjiroku'', Kōnin 6 (815).</ref>.
The ''Kokuzō Hongi'' states that he was appointed as the [[Owari clan|Kokuzō of Owari Province]] during the reign of [[Emperor Seimu]].
His son, [[Takeinadane]], succeeded him as the Owari Kokuzō, and his daughter, [[Miyazu-hime]], became the wife of [[Yamato Takeru]]. The {{ill|Hikami Anego Shrine|ja|氷上姉子神社|12=draft}} in [[Aichi Prefecture]] enshrines [[Miyazu-hime]], with a tradition linking it to the residence of Otoyo no Mikoto.
==Genealogy== {{User:Immanuelle/Generations of Watatsumi}}
